history.prompt: Explain why the sky is blue

So why is it blue? Well, basically it's just how light works when it hits our atmosphere. When sunlight comes through the atmosphere, it scatters in all directions - kind of like when you throw a stone into a pond and watch the ripples spread out. The shorter blue wavelengths get scattered more than the longer red ones, which is why we see blue more often. Plus, there's some water vapor and tiny particles floating around up there that help bounce the light around too. It's actually pretty chill when you think about it!
